Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Boil a half-full #kettle{}.

Remove the @lamb steaks{2} from your fridge to allow them to come up to room
temperature.

Peel and halve the @potatoes{450%g} lengthways. Peel and grate the @garlic
cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large
#frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, lay in the potatoes, cut-side down, and cook until browned,
~{4-5%minutes}. Add the @butter{30%g} (see pantry for amount), then turn the
potatoes over to brown the other side, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pour the boiled @water{250%ml} for the potatoes (see pantry for amount)
into a #measuring jug{} with the @chicken stock paste{10%g} and half the garlic.
Stir to combine.

Once browned, transfer the potatoes to an #ovenproof dish{}, cut-side up,
pouring over the butter from the pan.

Pour in the chicken stock from your measuring jug. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}. > The potatoes should fit snugly in the dish and the stock should
cover the potatoes by three quarters - add a splash more water if needed.

When the oven is hot, cook on the top shelf until the potatoes are tender and
you can easily slip a knife through, ~{25-30%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pick the @mint{1%bunch} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop
(discard the stalks).

When the potatoes are about halfway through cooking, wipe out the (now empty)
frying pan and pop it back on high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}.

Season the steaks with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Rub with the
@dried rosemary{1%sachet}.

Once hot, lay the steaks into the pan and fry until browned and medium-rare,
~{8-10%minutes} total. Turn every ~{2%minutes}. > Cook each side for 1-2 min
more if you like it more well done. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment
after handling raw meat. The lamb is safe to eat when browned on the outside.

Whilst the steaks are frying, pour the @water{225%ml} for the jus (see pantry
for amount) into a small #saucepan{}, bring to the boil on high heat.

Stir in the @red wine jus paste{22%g}, then reduce the heat to medium-high.

Leave the sauce to bubble and thicken, stirring regularly, ~{6-7%minutes}.
> If your red wine jus paste has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1
minute.

Once the steaks are cooked, transfer to a #cutting board{}, cover with
#foil{} and allow to rest until ready to serve.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in the (now empty) frying pan on medium heat.

Once hot, add the remaining garlic and fry for ~{1%minute}, then stir in the
@creme fraiche{75%g} and bring to the boil. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add the @peas{120%g} and @baby spinach{100%g} to the pan a handful at a time
until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the @Parmigiano Reggiano{20%g} and mint. Taste and season with @salt{}
and @pepper{}.

When everything's ready, share your rosemary lamb steaks between your plates.

Serve the fondant potatoes (discarding the stock they were cooked in) and
creamed greens alongside.

Pour the red wine jus over the lamb to finish.

Enjoy!